    contraindications: ['Hypersensitivity to olmesartan, hydrochlorothiazide, sulfonamides, or any component', 'Pregnancy (all trimesters) - FDA Boxed Warning', 'Anuria (inability to produce urine)', 'Severe renal impairment or kidney disease', 'Severe hepatic impairment', 'Hypersensitivity to sulfonamide-derived drugs', 'Concomitant use with aliskiren in diabetic patients'],
    warnings: ['Fetal toxicity: FDA Boxed Warning - Discontinue immediately if pregnancy detected', 'Hypotension: Monitor BP especially in volume-depleted patients', 'Sprue-like enteropathy: Severe chronic diarrhea with weight loss, villous atrophy', 'Electrolyte imbalances: Hypokalemia, hyponatremia, hypomagnesemia, hypercalcemia', 'Hyperuricemia and gout precipitation', 'Hyperglycemia and diabetes mellitus exacerbation', 'Acute angle-closure glaucoma and myopia', 'Renal function deterioration', 'Photosensitivity reactions', 'Systemic lupus erythematosus activation'],
    sideEffects: ['Common (>3%): Dizziness (9%), upper respiratory infection (7%), hyperuricemia (4%), nausea (3%)', 'Cardiovascular: Hypotension, chest pain, palpitations', 'Gastrointestinal: Severe diarrhea with weight loss, abdominal pain, vomiting', 'Metabolic: Hypokalemia, hyperglycemia, hyponatremia, hyperuricemia', 'Neurological: Headache, fatigue, weakness, paresthesia', 'Dermatologic: Photosensitivity, rash, purpura', 'Musculoskeletal: Back pain, joint pain, muscle cramps', 'Genitourinary: Polyuria, nocturia, impotence', 'Ocular: Blurred vision, acute myopia, angle-closure glaucoma', 'Rare but serious: Angioedema, severe hypotension, acute renal failure, pancreatitis, thrombocytopenia'],
    interactions: ['NSAIDs (aspirin, ibuprofen): Reduced antihypertensive effect, increased nephrotoxicity risk', 'Lithium: Increased lithium levels and toxicity risk', 'Potassium supplements/ACE inhibitors: Risk of hyperkalemia', 'Antidiabetic agents: HCTZ may increase blood glucose', 'Digitalis glycosides: Hypokalemia increases digitalis toxicity', 'Cholestyramine/colestipol: Reduced HCTZ absorption', 'Alcohol/barbiturates: Enhanced orthostatic hypotension', 'Corticosteroids/ACTH: Intensified electrolyte depletion', 'Pressor amines: Decreased response to norepinephrine', 'Skeletal muscle relaxants: Enhanced neuromuscular blocking effects'],
    pregnancy: 'FDA Boxed Warning - Pregnancy Category D: Contraindicated in all trimesters. Drugs acting on the renin-angiotensin system can cause fetal and neonatal morbidity and mortality including renal failure, oligohydramnios, intrauterine growth restriction, and death. Discontinue immediately if pregnancy is detected and switch to alternative antihypertensive therapy safe in pregnancy.',
    storage: 'Store at 20-25°C (68-77°F) with excursions permitted to 15-30°C (59-86°F). Protect from light and moisture. Keep in original container. Do not remove from blister until ready to use. Keep out of reach of children.',
    laymanExplanations: {
      description: 'A combination blood pressure medication that contains two different medicines working together: olmesartan (which blocks hormones that tighten blood vessels) and hydrochlorothiazide (a water pill that helps kidneys remove excess salt and water). This combination is particularly effective because it works through two different pathways to lower blood pressure and reduce the risk of heart attack and stroke.',
      mechanism: 'Olmesartan blocks a hormone called angiotensin II that normally makes blood vessels narrow and tight, while hydrochlorothiazide helps your kidneys remove extra salt and water from your body through increased urination. Together, these two actions reduce the amount of fluid in your blood vessels and make them more relaxed, which lowers blood pressure.',
      indications: ['Prescribed for high blood pressure when one medicine alone isn\'t working well enough', 'Used to reduce risk of heart attack, stroke, and other heart problems', 'Particularly helpful for people who retain fluid and have high blood pressure', 'Often used when blood pressure remains high despite taking a single medication', 'May be prescribed for people with diabetes and high blood pressure'],
      contraindications: ['Cannot be used during pregnancy as it can seriously harm or kill the unborn baby - this is a serious FDA warning', 'Should not be used if allergic to either medicine or sulfa drugs', 'Cannot be used if you cannot produce urine (anuria)', 'Not suitable for people with severe kidney or liver disease', 'Should not be used if you have severe allergic reactions to sulfonamide medications'],
      sideEffects: ['Most common: dizziness (especially when standing up), upper respiratory infections like colds, increased uric acid levels, nausea', 'Urinary effects: increased urination, especially when starting treatment', 'Heart-related: low blood pressure, chest pain, irregular heartbeat', 'Digestive: severe diarrhea with weight loss (rare but serious), stomach pain, vomiting', 'Blood chemistry changes: low potassium, high blood sugar, low sodium', 'Other effects: headache, tiredness, muscle cramps, back pain, skin sensitivity to sunlight', 'Serious but rare: severe allergic reactions, kidney problems, eye problems including glaucoma'],
      interactions: ['Tell your doctor about all medicines, vitamins, and supplements you take', 'Pain relievers like ibuprofen can reduce effectiveness and harm kidneys', 'Heart medicines like digoxin may need dose adjustments due to potassium changes', 'Diabetes medicines may need adjustment as this medication can raise blood sugar', 'Lithium levels can become dangerous - requires close monitoring', 'Potassium supplements may cause dangerous high potassium levels', 'Limit alcohol as it can increase dizziness and low blood pressure', 'Cholesterol medicines like cholestyramine can reduce effectiveness if taken together'],
      dosageAndAdmin: 'Take once daily at the same time each day, with or without food. Swallow the tablet whole - don\'t crush, chew, or break it. If you miss a dose, take it as soon as you remember, but skip it if it\'s almost time for your next dose. Never take two doses at once. Your doctor will start with a specific dose based on your previous blood pressure treatment.',
      warnings: ['May cause dizziness, especially when you first start taking it or when getting up quickly', 'Will make you urinate more, especially when starting treatment', 'Tell your doctor immediately if you become pregnant - this medicine can seriously harm your baby', 'Contact your doctor if you experience severe diarrhea with weight loss', 'May increase blood sugar levels - important for people with diabetes', 'Can cause sun sensitivity - use sunscreen and protective clothing', 'Regular blood tests needed to check kidney function and blood chemistry', 'Watch for signs of dehydration, especially in hot weather or during illness'],
      pregnancy: 'Absolutely must not be used during pregnancy - FDA Boxed Warning. Can cause serious birth defects, kidney failure, and death of the unborn baby. Use effective birth control and tell your doctor immediately if you become pregnant while taking this medicine.',
      storage: 'Keep at room temperature away from heat, moisture, and light. Store in the original packaging. Keep out of reach of children and pets. Do not use if the packaging is damaged or if tablets look different than usual.'
    }
